In this first English-language work to fully explore Hitler's influence on and relationship with film in Nazi Germany, the author calls on a broad array of archival sources. Arguing that Hitler was as central to the Nazi film industry as Goebbels, Niven also explores Hitler's representation in Third Reich cinema, personally and through films focusing on historical figures with whom he was associated, and how Hitler's vision for the medium went far beyond "straight propaganda." He aimed to raise documentary film to a powerful art form rivaling architecture in its ability to reach the masses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aMotion picture industryzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picture industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures in propagandazGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures, AmericanzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures, GermanzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism and motion pictures. 0aNazis in motion pictures. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2018z978311063899840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300235395423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300235395.jpg  a978-3-11-063899-8  YUP eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles